library(corrplot)

ANSWER: By using the corrplot package to plot the correlation matrix, we can see that it looks like a candy contains chocolate is least likely to contain fruit; a candy contains chocolate is more likely to be a bar candy than a hard candy; and it looks like a candy contains chocolate is more likely to win.

5. Empirical Model

Write a multiple linear regression empirical model that was was estimated in the article. Intepret the coefficients in the context of the problem. What would it mean for a coefficient to be statistically significant? What is the assumptions made when using this linear model?

\[ winpercent = \beta_0 + \beta_1chocolate + \beta_2fruity+ \beta_3caramel + \beta_4 peanutyalmondy + \beta_5nougat + \beta_6crispedricewafer + \beta_6hard + \beta_7bar + \beta_8pluribus +\varepsilon \]

ANSWER: In the article, the authors created a linear model of winpercent using all the other variables (except competitorname, sugarpercent, pricepercent). We can see the coefficients between winpercent and some other variables shown below. The coefficients mean that if a hypothetical candy had chocolate in it, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about 19.91 points; if its fruity, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about 10.27 points; if it has peanuts, peanut butter, or almond, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about by 10.14 points; if it has wafers or crisped rice, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about by 8.99 points; if it has caramel, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about by 3.38 points; if it has nougat, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about by 2.42 points. On the other hand, a candy being hard like a lollipop or jawbreaker actually knocks about 4.87 points off its win percentage. Whether its in bar form or a bunch of little candies makes no major difference (only expect its win percentage to drop by 0.72 points and 0.16 points respectively). A coefficient would be considered to be statistically significant when its p-value equal to or lower than 5%, and a coefficient is statistically significant means that changes in the predictor are associated with changes in the response. When using this linear model, we assume that 1)there is a linear relationship between the dependent variable winprecent and each of the independent variables; 2)the independent variables are not highly correlated with each other; 3)the amount of error in the residuals is similar at each point of the linear model;4) the observations should be independent of one another.

win_model <- lm(winpercent ~ chocolate + fruity + caramel + peanutyalmondy + nougat + crispedricewafer + hard + bar +pluribus, data = candy_rankings)

7. Discussion

Interpret your results from question 6. Did the model explain much of the variation in the dependent variable? Do you feel like anything may have been omitted from the regression that should have been included?

ANSWER: According to the table from question 6, we can see that R-square is 0.515, which indicates that this model explains 51.5% the variability of the response data around its mean. And, we can see that only four variables-chocolate, fruity, peanutyalmondy, and crispedricewafer have significant impact on variable winpercent. Also, the coefficients mean that if a hypothetical candy had chocolate in it, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about 19.906 points; if its fruity, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about 10.268 points; if it has peanuts, peanut butter, or almond, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about by 10.141 points; if it has wafers or crisped rice, we would expect its win percentage to rise by about by 8.992 points. However, this model may omit some other variables like pricepercent and sugarpercent that should have been included. We can just do a quick check by just add variables pricepercent and sugarpercent to the model (we exclude competitorname here because it is a categorical variable with a unique value in every row of the data set, its actually mathematically impossible to fit a linear model with it.) We find R-square of the new model is 0.540, which indicates that this model explains 54% the variability of the response data around its mean, which is slightly better than first model, we may still need to improve the model through other ways.

win_model_2 <- lm(winpercent ~ . -competitorname, data = candy_rankings)
